observations.managementAction:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the:

a.  Creation of an inventory committee; 

b.  GSO to properly plan and conduct the physical count of all PPEs and ensure timely submission of complete RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor; 

c. GSO to conduct of inventory of all unserviceable properties and prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) to facilitate and expedite the disposal of all unserviceable properties;

d. GSO to update Property Cards (PCs) to record all procurement and disposals of PPEs so that a reconciliation between the PCs with the physical count can be made; and,

e. Municipal Accountant and the GSO to conduct periodic reconciliation of the accounting and property records with the physical count and make the necessary provision for depreciation and adjustments for any discrepancies noted, for accurate and fair presentation of PPE account balances in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

a.  Direct the creation of inventory committee, conduct timely physical inventory and prepare the RPCI;

b.  Require the Designated Supply Custodian/ General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete stock cards and supplies ledger cards, respectively and to reconcile the same;

c.  Require the Municipal Accountant to properly record the purchases of inventories in the appropriate inventory accounts and the consumption thereof as expense, in accordance with the IPSAS 17; and
d.  Henceforth, comply with pertinent provisions relative to the receipt, recording, issuance and distribution of inventories held for distribution.

We recommended the following:

a. Organize and fill-in the vacant positions in the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Office as prescribed by Section 12 of RA 10121, dated May 27, 2010 and pertinent guidelines embodied in NDRRMC, DILG, DBM, and CSC Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2014-1, so that programs and projects pertaining to DRRM will be carried out efficiently and effectively; 

b. Make appropriately correct the designation and/ or appointment of the LDRRM Officer.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct concerned officials and employees to:
Design a well-planned procurement program that would limit the use of alternative methods in the procurement of meals;
Ensure that Purchase Requests, Requests for Quotations and Purchase Orders for meals are duly supported with food specifications to justify the reasonableness of prices indicated therein; and
Comply with the posting requirements provided in Annex H Consolidated Guidelines for the Alternative Methods of Procurement and Section 54.3 of the IRR of RA No. 9184;
The aforementioned audit observation was communicated to management thru Audit Observation Memorandum No. 2022-012 dated April 19, 2022.

observations.managementAction:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the Municipal Accountant to:

a.	Review the previous years’ transactions, secure the documents supporting the prior years’ reconciling items and cause the immediate recording of the reconciling items particularly those which persisted in the BRS for a long period;

b.	For current year and onwards, analyze and verify discrepancies/ errors and other reconciling items immediately after the preparation of the monthly BRS, and prepare JEV for corrections/adjustments in the GL to present accurate balances of the cash in bank accounts;

c.	Enroll all the Municipality’s accounts under the LBP weAccess facility for early viewing of transactions and to obtain copy/ies of bank statements. For other bank accounts, undertake measures to address the cause/s of delay in the preparation of the monthly BRS;and

d.	Submit to the Auditor the monthly BRS of various Cash in Bank-LCCA SL balances without BRS, and henceforth ensure that monthly BRS of all bank accounts are submitted to the Audit Team within the prescribed period pursuant to COA Circular No. 96-011 and Section 74 of P.D. No. 1445.

We recommended that Management:

a. Take heed of the basic controls in the receipt, recording and utilization of cash donations received;

Prepare and submit a Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances as well as proof of receipt by and distribution to the beneficiaries for cash donation received in compliance with COA Circular No. 2020-009;

Maintain a separate bank account with an authorized government depository bank (AGDB) where cash donations are to be deposited; and

Submit the required reports together with the supporting documents.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere with Section 4 (sub-sections 1-2, 4 and 6) of the Government Auditing Code of the Philippines (P.D. No. 1445). Further, we require the following: 

1) SB Resolution approving the foreign travel and its attendant expenses; 
2) Authority to travel for government personnel per EO 298 prescribing the rules and regulations on local and foreign travels;
 3) Approval of the Municipal Mayor of the travel including the list of the delegation; 
4) Justification/explanation as to the status of refund of expenses by Iloilo International; 
5) Certified complete list of the delegation together with the cultural performers; 
6) Certification by school head/principal that the performers were enrollees of the government school/s; 7) Certificate of Appearance/Participation of the delegation certified by Iloilo International and/or authorized official of the government of Guam; 
8) Liquidation Reports by the Disbursing Officer on cash advances granted relative to the foreign travel, including journal entry vouchers to take up the liquidations; 
9) Submission of documents/requirements to the deficiencies noted in Annex 2; and 
10) Justification as to the efficiency, effectiveness and economy of the disbursements relative to the travel to Guam, USA.

observations.recommendation:
Recommendations
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct the:
Creation of an inventory committee;
GSO to properly plan and conduct the physical count of all PPEs and ensure timely submission of complete RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor;
GSO to conduct of inventory of all unserviceable properties and prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) to facilitate and expedite the disposal of all unserviceable properties;
GSO to maintain complete duly accomplished updated PCs to record all procurement and disposals of PPEs so that a reconciliation between the PCs with the physical count can be made; and
Municipal Accountant and the GSO to conduct periodic reconciliation of the accounting and property records with the physical count and make the necessary adjustments on any discrepancies noted, for accurate and fair presentation of PPE account balances in the financial statements.
The aforementioned audit observation was communicated to management thru Audit Observation Memorandum No. 2021-009 dated March 25, 2021.
